SECTION 4 — WEAKNESSES
================================================================================

METADATA INCONSISTENCY

  [-] paper/paper.tex — \paperrepository points to wrong URL
      Found:    https://github.com/egohygiene/papers
      Expected: https://github.com/egohygiene/reflector
      Impact:   The wrong repository URL appears in the compiled PDF title block
                and PDF metadata. This is a publication-facing error.

  [-] README.md is essentially empty
      The root README.md contains only 2 lines (title + emoji tagline).
      No description, build instructions, or publication links are present.
      This is the first thing visitors and GitHub bots see.

  [-] CHANGELOG.md does not exist
      The release-paper.yml workflow validates CHANGELOG.md before creating a
      GitHub Release and will fail with a hard error if it is missing.
      release-please will generate CHANGELOG.md on first release PR merge, but
      until then, any manual tag-triggered release will fail.

PUBLICATION INFRASTRUCTURE GAPS

  [-] docs/figures/ directory missing — hero.png not deployed to Pages
      docs/index.html references ./figures/hero.png (relative path).
      The pages.yml workflow copies docs/ to _site/ but does NOT copy
      paper/figures/hero.png into _site/figures/.
      Result: The hero image will be a broken link on the deployed Pages site.

  [-] docs/index.html references reflector-latest.pdf
      pages.yml creates both reflector.pdf and reflector-latest.pdf in docs/.
      However, if docs/ is committed without these PDFs present, the links
      will be broken until the workflow runs.

  [-] pages.yml verification step does not check for _site/figures/hero.png
      The required-file list checks for _site/reflector.pdf and
      _site/publication.json but does not verify the hero image is present.

RELEASE WORKFLOW GAPS

  [-] release-please.yml uses skip-github-release: true
      This means release-please manages version PRs but does NOT create
      GitHub Releases itself. The actual release depends on:
        1. Merging the release-please PR (updates VERSION, CHANGELOG.md)
        2. Manually pushing a matching git tag (e.g., v0.0.1)
        3. That tag triggering release-paper.yml
      This two-step process (PR merge + manual tag push) is fragile and
      not self-documenting. The release-please PR does not automatically
      push a tag if skip-github-release is true; the tag must be pushed
      separately after the PR merges.

  [-] No mechanism connects release-please PR merge to tag push
      Without a tag-creation step (or using skip-github-release: false),
      the release-paper.yml workflow will never be triggered automatically.
      The release pipeline is currently a dead end in terms of automation.

PAPER CONTENT GAPS

  [-] 15 of 16 paper sections are empty TODO stubs
      Only abstract.tex contains substantive content.
      All other sections (introduction, recursive_ai_systems, recursive_drift,
      synchronization, reflective_auditing, milestone_execution,
      reflector_framework, operational_demonstration, limitations, conclusion,
      visual_summary, appendix, related_work, implementation_examples,
      case_studies) contain only a section header, label, TODO comment, and
      an intended figure placeholder comment.

  [-] All bibliography entries are placeholder entries
      references.bib contains 3 placeholder citations with note fields
      indicating they must be replaced with real references.
      The paper cannot be submitted to arXiv or any venue with placeholder
      citations.

IMPLEMENTATION GAPS

  [-] reflector/ Python package is entirely unimplemented
      All 8 subdirectories contain only .gitkeep. __init__.py is empty.
      No Python modules, classes, schemas, or CLI entry points exist.

  [-] demos/ directory is entirely unimplemented
      All 3 demo subdirectories contain only .gitkeep.

  [-] No pyproject.toml, setup.py, or requirements.txt
      The reflector/ Python package has no project configuration.
      It cannot be installed or used as a package.

DOCUMENTATION GAPS

  [-] CONTRIBUTING.md references a "templates/paper/" directory
      that does not appear to exist at the repository root.
      scaffold-paper.sh also references this template and would fail
      if run without the templates/ directory present.

  [-] scripts/scaffold-paper.sh only accepts "paper" or "reflector" as slugs
      The validation is unnecessarily restrictive for a general-purpose
      scaffold tool. The paper/ directory already exists, so running
      scaffold-paper.sh would fail regardless.

================================================================================
SECTION 5 — SYNCHRONIZATION GAPS
================================================================================

GAP 1 — Wrong repository URL in paper.tex
  paper/paper.tex:\paperrepository → https://github.com/egohygiene/papers
  Expected                         → https://github.com/egohygiene/reflector
  Affected surfaces: compiled PDF, PDF metadata, Pages-deployed PDF

GAP 2 — Hero image not included in Pages deployment
  Source:       paper/figures/hero.png
  Referenced:   docs/index.html → ./figures/hero.png
  Deployed via: pages.yml → cp docs/. _site/ (does NOT copy paper/figures/)
  Missing step: Copy paper/figures/hero.png → docs/figures/hero.png
                (either committed or added to pages.yml sync step)

GAP 3 — CHANGELOG.md missing; release workflow will fail
  Required by:  release-paper.yml (validates CHANGELOG entry for version)
  Status:       File does not exist in repository
  Impact:       Any release tag push will immediately fail with hard error

GAP 4 — release-please → release-paper.yml automation gap
  release-please manages version bumps and PR creation
  release-paper.yml triggers on tag push
  Missing link: release-please PR merge does NOT push a tag automatically
                when skip-github-release: true is set
  Impact:       Release pipeline is not fully automated end-to-end

GAP 5 — Root publication.json vs docs/publication.json divergence
  Root publication.json:    static file committed to repo (status: draft)
  docs/publication.json:    dynamically generated at pages deploy time
  These serve different purposes but could cause confusion about
  which is the authoritative publication state document.

GAP 6 — Version metadata across three files
  VERSION file:                    0.0.1
  .release-please-manifest.json:   {"." : "0.0.1"}
  CITATION.cff:                    version: 0.0.1
  These are currently in sync, but all three must be updated together
  on every release. release-please automates this via extra-files config.

GAP 7 — docs/ and paper/figures/ are separate hierarchies
  docs/index.html assumes ./figures/hero.png exists under docs/
  paper/figures/ contains the actual hero.png asset
  No workflow step, symlink, or committed copy bridges this gap

GAP 8 — build-paper.yml triggers include pages.yml and release-paper.yml as paths
  build-paper.yml triggers on changes to:
    .github/workflows/pages.yml
    .github/workflows/release-paper.yml
  This causes a paper build CI run to trigger when only deployment or
  release workflows change (no paper content changed). Minor but noisy.

GAP 9 — pages.yml rebuilds LaTeX instead of consuming build-paper.yml artifact
  pages.yml runs xu-cheng/latex-action@v3 independently from build-paper.yml.
  There is no dependency or artifact-sharing between the two workflows.
  The same PDF may be built twice on the same commit. This is by design
  (decoupled workflows) but creates a latency and cost gap.

GAP 10 — reflector/ package has no connection to paper content
  The paper describes the reflector framework conceptually.
  The reflector/ Python package is scaffolded to implement it.
  There is currently no traceability between paper sections and
  implementation modules (e.g., paper/sections/reflective_auditing.tex
  vs reflector/audits/).

